Analysis of Attitudes about Mental Health in the Tech Workforce

¶

Amoni Hawkins
¶

Introduction

The objective of this project is to analyze data from a 2014 and 2016 survey that measures the general attitudes towards mental health and its occurrence within a tech company. I hope to inform this specific demographic of employees within the tech industry about what could be the strongest predictors of this illness that relays its occurrence.

Throughout my tutorial, I will be trying to find any correlations and trends between different mental health benefits and consequences, the availability of care options depending on company type and so much more. Within my mining, I hope to protray results that demonstrate how such attitudes may be formed.

Data Collection
¶

I will be collecting and scraping data from Kaggle (which is a data science company full of public datasets) found specifically at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/osmi/mental-health-in-tech-survey?resource=download & https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/osmi/mental-health-in-tech-2016 and formatting it into a dataframe so that it is easy to both visualize and alter for exploratory analysis. The datasets have been downlaoded into a CSV or Comma Separated Value file. I will be using different Python3 libraries to acheive this such as numpy, pandas, and more.

I used the pandas.read_csv function to read in both of the csv files and stored them into separate Dataframes. I have displayed the head of the Dataframe from the 2014 survey and have displayed its 27 columns. Some columns are not self-explanatory, so I will list out the survey questions that pertains to column names as provided from the website.

  • mental_health_consequence: Do you think that discussing a mental health issue with your employer would have negative consequences?
  • phys_health_consequence: Do you think that discussing a physical health issue with your employer would have negative consequences?
  • coworkers: Would you be willing to discuss a mental health issue with your coworkers?
  • supervisor: Would you be willing to discuss a mental health issue with your direct supervisor(s)?
  • mental_health_interview: Would you bring up a mental health issue with a potential employer in an interview?
  • phys_health_interview: Would you bring up a physical health issue with a potential employer in an interview?

Data Tidying and Management
¶

In this phase of The Data Science Pipeline, I will be tidying up the data to make it more readable and strengthen the organization of my dataframes. This will make the exploratory anaylsis easier because I have better navigation of all of the information.

In [5]:
survey_2014.drop(["Timestamp", "comments"], axis = 1, inplace = True) # get rid of unnecessary columns
survey_2014["Gender"] = np.where((survey_2014["Gender"] == "Male") | (survey_2014["Gender"] == "m") | (survey_2014["Gender"] == "male")
                                 , "M", survey_2014["Gender"])
survey_2014["Gender"] = np.where((survey_2014["Gender"] == "Female") | (survey_2014["Gender"] == "f") | (survey_2014["Gender"] == "female")
                                 , "F", survey_2014["Gender"])
survey_2014 = survey_2014.rename(columns=str.lower)

For the 2014 dataframe, I have removed the columns of "Timeframe" and "comments", because these particular columns were not needed for my analysis. This tidies the data as the comments column had different sporadic values, which would be hard to visualize for analytical purposes. In order to better represent the genders of Male and Female, I have condensed the various ways in which these two genders were expressed to just M and F; there were other answers such as "non binary" that I left as is. I converted the column names to lowercase for simplicity and uniformity.

Although the column names for the 2016 survey were easy to interpret because they were questions, to further tidy this data I will rename these columns to make the dataframe more concise. The list of the columns before tidying is below:

Exploratory Data Analysis
¶

In this phase of The Data Science Pipeline, I will plot my data and exploit trends along different variables from both of the surveys. I will be investigating these datasets in hopes of observing patterns, outliers and understanding the data to form hypotheses. Most of the data collected within these datasets are not of numerical value, so I will be looking at the frequency of responses moreso than manipulating any numbers (operations such as max).

I will be exploring the data from the surveys seperately and then ultimate look at their trends together. Below is my exploration of the 2014 data:

2014¶

Graphing Frequency of Difficulty of Asking for Leave based on Type of Company¶

In [9]:
survey_2014.value_counts(["tech_company", "leave"]).reset_index().sort_values(["tech_company", "leave"]).set_index('leave').plot(kind = 'bar', figsize = (15,10))

plt.title("Frequency of Difficulty of Asking for Leave vs Type of Company")
plt.xlabel("Difficulty")
plt.ylabel("Frequency of Response")
survey_2014.value_counts(["tech_company", "leave"]).reset_index().sort_values(["tech_company", "leave"]).set_index('leave')

Up above, I have graphed the frequency of survey responses to the survey question: "How easy is it for you to take medical leave for a mental health condition?" based on if the company was in the tech industry or not. As similar to the small data table above it, the first 5 bars of the graph pertain to if the company was not tech-related. Based on these results, not many employees working for a tech company are sure of the difficulty (most likely because they have not done so), yet most responses say that it is somewhat easy to ask. The frequency of the easy responses within a tech company are larger than companies that aren't.

Correlation Between Anonymity and Supervisor Interaction¶

Does increased anonymity make it easier to talk to supervisor about mental health issues?

In [10]:
survey_2014.value_counts(["anonymity", "supervisor"]).reset_index().sort_values(["anonymity", "supervisor"]).set_index('supervisor').plot(kind = 'bar', figsize = (15,10))
plt.title("Willingness to talk to Supervisor about Mental Health vs Anonymity Status")
plt.xlabel("Willingness to talk to Supervisor about Mental Health")
plt.ylabel("Frequency of Response")
survey_2014.value_counts(["anonymity", "supervisor"]).reset_index().sort_values(["anonymity", "supervisor"]).set_index('supervisor')
Out[10]:

Again, we are comparing the frequency of these responses to see if the protection of being anonymous when receiving treatment resources affects whether employees feel comfortable sharing mental health issues with their supervisors. In accordance to the responses of "Don't Know", "No", and "Yes" respectively, each section of 3 bars corresponds to this answer about whether an individual's anonymity is protected at their company. Even though workers are unware of their protection, the highest frequency recorded of 298 responses went to "Yes". As expected, the values are a lot lower when it is known that their information does not remain anonymous. Is oblivion a better state in this case?

Geographic Location as an Indicator of Mental Health¶

In [11]:
latitude = 37.0902
longitude = -95.7129
US_map = folium.Map(location=[latitude, longitude], zoom_start=4.5)

for index, row in (survey_2014[survey_2014['country'] == "United States"]).iterrows():
    if row["family_history"] == "Yes":
        state = row["state"]
        geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="MyApp")
        location = geolocator.geocode(state)
        folium.Marker(location=[location.latitude, location.longitude],
                icon=folium.Icon(color='blue')).add_to(US_map)
US_map
Out[11]:
Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

As we can see with the graph of the United States, individuals who lived along the East Coast more heavily reported having a family history of mental illness. Surprisingly, there was not a single marker within the state of California. This is shocking as California is both heavily populated and a popular place for tech companies.

Here we are looking at what percent of work time or productivity is affected due to improper or proper treatment of an individual's mental illness. The bar charts are broken up into four sections depending on percentages: 1-25%, 26-50%, 51-75%, and 76%-100%. We can see that when treated effectively, the reponses are higher in range of the 1-25% area, whereas when not treated effectively it has more responses in 26%-50% range.

In comparison, we see that over the span of two years that employees were still unsure if their employer took mental health and its issues just as serious as physical health. For both years as well, there were more responses for not observing any negative consequences who were open about their mental health issues. In 2016, there was a rise in the number of No responses when employees felt that their employer took mental health just as seriously.

As gathered from my exploratory analysis, discussing mental health is multi-faceted and numerous factors play roles in the overall outlook and attitude towards this topic in the workforce in general.

Hypothesis Testing

During this phase of The Data Science Pipeline, we will try to perform various modeling techniques on our data in order to get a predictive model for possible trends. We will use a Linear Regression Model, which is a machine learning technique, to get a better understanding and see if the size of a company influences factors such as anonymity or access to benefits.

survey_2014["no_employees"] = np.where((survey_2014["no_employees"] == "1-5"), 0, survey_2014["no_employees"])
survey_2014["no_employees"] = np.where((survey_2014["no_employees"] == "6-25"), 1, survey_2014["no_employees"])
survey_2014["no_employees"] = np.where((survey_2014["no_employees"] == "26-100"), 2, survey_2014["no_employees"])
survey_2014["no_employees"] = np.where((survey_2014["no_employees"] == "100-500"), 3, survey_2014["no_employees"])
survey_2014["no_employees"] = np.where((survey_2014["no_employees"] == "500-1000"), 4, survey_2014["no_employees"])
survey_2014["no_employees"] = np.where((survey_2014["no_employees"] == "More than 1000"), 5, survey_2014["no_employees"])

#rewrite anonymous status
survey_2014["anonymity"] = np.where((survey_2014["anonymity"] == "Don't know"), 0, survey_2014["anonymity"])
survey_2014["anonymity"] = np.where((survey_2014["anonymity"] == "No"), 1, survey_2014["anonymity"])
survey_2014["anonymity"] = np.where((survey_2014["anonymity"] == "Yes"), 2, survey_2014["anonymity"])

Conclusion and Insights Attained
¶

Even though mental health affects workers in all companies, I decided to dedicate my project to those attitudes that specifically generate within the tech workforce. As a Black woman in STEM, I found personal connections with this topic and hope to find correlations that could be useful to my own experience. Both the stigma and lack of knowledge about mental health contributes to these overall negative perceptions as seen in the frequency of certain responses. I learned about interpretating data even when it does not always present itself in a numerical form. Even if you are not in the tech industry, the information I worked with and how I manipulated it could translate to other datasets in terms of visualizing trends of human social behavior.

If you are interested more about mental health (not just in the workforce context), there are a lot of datasets to explore and articles to read such as https://www.kaggle.com/search?q=mental+health+in%3Adatasets and https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=articles+about+mental+health&hl=en&as_sdt=0&as_vis=1&oi=scholart where you can further educate yourself. Some common myths such as negative career impact due to mental illness were debunked as seen in my chart as those who actually had the illness did not reflect that belief or attitude. If further analysis was conducted, we could look into and explore more about how other social characteristics such as race and ethnicity come into play especially within the tech industry. I hope my tutorial was worth the read and sparked curiosity!
